observations.recommendation:
We recommended, and Management agreed to direct the:
Inventory Committee to:
Conduct the one-time physical inventory of PPEs under the name of the LGU and relieve each member of their regular functions to devote themselves in completing the same;

Prepare the PIP, and submit the same to the Municipal Mayor for approval to ensure  the proper and adequate conduct of inventory-taking pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006;

Submit a copy of the approved PIP to COA at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;

Use pre-numbered property stickers bearing the vital information on the PPE items;

Prepare a consolidated RPCPPE to be used for the reconciliation of PPE items recorded in the GSO and Accounting Office;

Strictly implement COA Circular No. 2020-006 in the conduct of inventory of PPE.

Municipal Treasurer as the Designated Municipal GSO to:
Use pre-numbered property tags or control stickers to all PPE containing the information required under Section 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 and attach the same to the prominent and secured portion of the inventoried PPE for proper and easy identification;

Ensure that all issuances of PPE items are covered with PARs as prescribed under Section 5.6 of COA Circular No. 2020-006; and


Renew/Update issued PARs every three (3) years after issuance or whenever there is a change in custodianship to establish proper accountability;

Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Accountant and Inventory Committee to coordinate and complete the physical inventory-taking and conduct the reconciliation of the RPCPPE; identify and address the nature and causes of variances; and hold responsible/accountable the designated officers/custodian;

Municipal Accountant to record adjustments after completion of proper reconciliation to establish the correct balances of PPE and other affected accounts, with the presence of valid supporting documents.

We recommended, and the management agreed to instruct the BAC to:
Evaluate each procurement request from different departments and properly determine the appropriate and correct procurement mode;

Refrain from utilizing the Shopping method for procurement transactions if they do not meet the conditions specified in cases a and b of Section 52 in the RIRR of RA No. 9184;

Consider the application of Negotiated procurement through the SVP method under Section 53.9 of RIRR, RA 9184, if all conditions are met; and

Indicate in the PO the important details such as the Mode of Procurement, and the Date and the Terms of Delivery to comply with COA Circular No. 96-010.

We recommended, and the management agreed to direct;
The Municipal Accountant to regularly monitor the movement of the CAs of concerned Accountable Officers in order to restrict the granting of additional CAs to those with unliquidated CAs, and ensure the timely liquidation of the same and continue issuing demand letters requiring the liquidation of CAs to the AOs concerned; and

The Municipal Treasurer to withhold the salaries of the Accountable Officers with unliquidated CAs until such time that the CAs are fully liquidated.

To strengthen management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the LCE institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

to conduct risk assessment; 

to identify critical processes and functions; 

to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 

to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 

to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and

to submit a plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

We recommended, and the management agreed to require the Municipal Accountant to apply the criteria on capitalization of PPE as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2022-004 to ensure proper classification of assets in the books and draw a Journal Entry Voucher to effect necessary adjustments in the books of accounts in CY 2024.

The Municipal Treasurer to:

Provide data to the Municipal Accountant relevant to items reclassified as semi-expendable property including information of its condition;

Update existing PPE and Inventory records and prepare and maintain the additional necessary forms/reports/registries for purposes of record-keeping, and monitoring  over issued semi-expendable properties provided in Section 4 of the Circular;

Cancel the PAR of the semi-expendable property and issue an Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) to the actual custodian of the items; and

Moving forward, issue ICS to actual custodians of items to establish monitoring, control and accountability over them.

