The management to:

Direct the personnel concerned in providing the necessary data on the transactions presented as to the basic information of the description of the items and the quantity of goods received by the beneficiaries;

Monitor the Property Officer/Custodian on the preparation and maintenance of necessary reports and inventory list of all procured and donated items in accordance with COA Circular No. 2014-002 dated April 15, 2014.

Recommendations
We recommended, and the management agreed to instruct the BAC to:
Evaluate each procurement request from different departments andproperly determine the appropriate and correct procurement mode;
Refrain from utilizing the Shopping method for procurement transactions if they do not meet the conditions specified in cases a and b of Section 52 in the RIRR of RA No. 9184;
Consider the application of Negotiated procurement through the SVP method under Section 53.9 of RIRR, RA 9184, if all conditions are met; and
Indicate in the PO the important details such as the Mode of Procurement, and the Date and the Terms of Delivery to comply with COA Circular No. 96-010.

The Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Engineer for documents such as Report on Completed Projects and Certificate of Project Completion as basis in reclassifying or transferring of CIP to its appropriate asset account. Further, to record necessary adjustments in the books of accounts based on the result of verification to reflect the correct balance of the account;

The Municipal Engineer to submit the Statement of Work Accomplished (SWA) as one of the documentary requirements in payment for infrastructure project carried out under “by Administration”; and

The Municipal Engineering Office submit and coordinate timely with the  Municipal Accounting Office on the status of the on-going and completed projects at least quarterly to regularly reconcile projects accomplishment.

The Municipal Government enhance its compliance with policies and procedures on Local Roads Asset Management System by:

Direct the members of Inventory Committee as an initial step, to conduct Inventory count and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network;

Direct the members of Inventory Committee to properly segregate and classify all road networks and its components;

Provide cost to specific Road Network and its components in order to have proper valuation and completeness of the Road Network Account;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to establish and properly maintain the Local Road Network Property Card for all Road networks and its components; using the RCPPE reports as basis;

Monitor proper reconciliation between Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network and Local Road Network Ledger Card and/ Property Card and make the necessary adjustments; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant the proper disclosure in the Financial Statement of Road Network System.

Recommendation:
We recommended that management direct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Conduct physical count of all inventories held by the Municipality, and submit a properly accomplished RPCI by type/classification on a regular basis for the succeeding semesters and coordinate with the Municipal Accountant for the reconciliation and adjustment of the related inventory accounts;
Maintain Stock Cards of all inventory items and to record the receipt and issuance thereof, in accordance with the Government Accounting Manual;
Require the end-user to promptly prepare and submit to the Accountant the monthly Report of Supplies and Materials Issued RMSSI), duly supported with RIS, ICS and other proofs   of goods distribution so that issuance thereof is timely recorded and accounted for in the books of accounts.

Recommendation:
We recommend the LCE to:
Create and Inventory Committee with adequate number of members and representatives from the Accounting and Property Division/Unit;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to:
Prepare the Physical Inventory Plan (PIP), and submit the same to the Municipal Mayor to ensure that the conduct of inventory-taking is properly and adequately planned pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Submit a copy of the approved PIP to COA at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;
prioritize the completion of physical count of PPEs; and
prepare the RPCPPE, reconcile the same with the Property Division/Unit and Accounting Unit records
Instruct the Accounting Unit to prepare the necessary adjusting entries, if any, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006.

Recommendation:
We recommended that management:
Require the official drivers to timely and regularly prepare and submit duly accomplished and serially-numbered Driver’s Trip Tickets for each trip, Per-numbered gas Slip, and the corresponding copy of Delivery Receipt for control purposes. This document will show the details of the actual places visited, the actual distance traveled and the corresponding quantity of fuel consumed. A summary record of travel is prepared for every vehicle with complete supporting documents;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to timely and regularly prepare the Monthly Report of Official Travels and Monthly Fuel Consumption Report for monitoring and controlling purposes, and to submit these reports to the Auditor for verification and evaluation of the reasonableness of fuel consumption in a specific month;
Assign an official to closely monitor and control fuel consumption, and enjoin compliance with the above -stated regulations in order to properly account for the utilization of gasoline, oil and lubricants;
Direct the Municipal the Accountant to effect the necessary adjustments and comply strictly with the provisions of Sections 114 of the Manual on NGAS for the proper recording of purchased fuel, oil and lubricants; and
Direct the Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Accountant and other concerned officials to coordinate and exert extra effort to prepare and submit valid documents for liquidation of the year end balances that are still carried in the books as of December 31, 2021.

The Management to;

Refrain from using LDRRM Funds for administrative expenses which are not directly related to the purpose of the fund. The above provisions provide various programs and activities that could be considered as disaster preparation and mitigation activities which the management should be guided accordingly; and

Provide an appropriation for administrative expenditures of the LDRRM Office sourced from the General Fund of the LGU in order to maximize the utilization of the 5% LDRRM Funds.

