Set-up a special account the collection of fines, fees and other receipts arising from possible income of recyclable materials.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Accountant –Prepare lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each road and road components at the end of the year;
Municipal Treasurer– Local Road Inventory and Road Map and present complete Local Road Network Property Ledger Card for all roads and road components;
Inventory Committee – Report on the Physical Count of the Public Infrastructures of the LGU including the Road Network System.

We recommended that the municipality’s GAD Focal Point System shall conduct gender mainstreaming through gender audit and gender analysis of its policies, programs, services and the current situation of the municipality in terms of GAD compliance;
To equip the GFPS with the in-depth knowledge and capacity on GAD, it was also recommended that they shall undergo trainings and seminars such as those relating to gender-responsive planning and budgeting, gender analysis, gender audit and the use of various GAD tools for the LGU’s GAD implementation of PAPs; and
Revisit and strictly comply with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9710 and other provisions of law.

The Municipal Engineer provides an explanation as to why projects were not completed on their target completion dates together with the variation orders and the contractor’s notices;
The LGU through the Municipal Engineering Office and other concerned offices fast track the implementation of unfinished projects and consider the imposition of liquidated damages against contractors for unreasonable delays in the completion of projects;
The LGU direct all concerned to see to it that all transactions like procurement for projects must not be paid by the local government if not supported with complete documentation.
The Municipal Mayor, being the immediate and primary responsible for all financial transactions and operations entered into by the Municipality ensures that laws, rules and regulations shall be strictly complied.

Direct the DRRM Council to implement the LDRRM Plan according to the LDRRM Investment Plan approved for the year;
Direct the DRRM Council to come up with disaster risk management activities for the LGU in order to utilize the accumulated balance of LDRRM Fund in accordance with DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2012-73 which enjoined the Local Chief Executives to utilize their DRRM Fund to ensure that basic “rescue and response equipment” are procured and to operationalize the provisions of the National DRRM Plan and National Climate Change Action Plan;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer for the LDRRMF allocation as to the 30% Quick Response Fund and 70% Mitigation and Disaster Preparedness Fund; and
Facilitate the transfer/turn-over of the equipment to the new MDRRMO-Designate and issue corresponding Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment (ARE).

Comply the requirements and make a representation or follow-up for the approval of the SWM Plan of the LGU;
Strictly observe proper charging of expenses against the 20% development fund and solid waste management program; and
Set-up a special account the collection of fines, fees and other receipts arising from possible income of recyclable materials.

We recommended that the Management through the following heads of offices of the LGU furnish COA with the following documents as stated in the aforementioned COA Circulars:
Municipal Accountant – Registries of Public Infrastructures of                        P 89,269,453.73   classified by category of property, plant and equipment;
Municipal Treasurer  - Local Road Inventory and Road Map and present a complete Local Network Property Ledger Card for all roads and its components as prescribed in Annex E of COA Circular 2015-008;
Municipal Engineer – Report on the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects which was submitted to the Municipal Accountant as basis of recording Road Networks in the books of accounts at year-end; and
Inventory Committee – Report on the Physical Count of the Public Infrastructures of the LGU including Road Network System.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Engineer provide an explanation as to why projects were not completed on their target completion dates together with the variation orders and the contractors notices;
The LGU through the Municipal Engineering Office and other concerned offices fast track the implementation of unfinished projects and consider the imposition of liquidated damages against contractors for unreasonable delays in the completion of projects;
The LGU direct all concerned to see to that all transactions like procurements and/or projects must not be paid by the local government if not supported with complete documentation; and
The Municipal Mayor, being the immediate and primary responsible for all financial transactions and operations entered into by the Municipality, ensures that laws, rules and regulations shall be strictly complied.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Issue an Order directing the Municipal Planning Development Coordinator (MPDC) to lead the preparation and submission to COA of the Quarterly Report on Government PPAs since it is one of his duties to monitor and evaluate the implementation of the different development programs, projects, and activities in the local government unit concerned in accordance with the approved development plan;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to prepare and maintain a Monthly Monitoring Report to keep track of the progress of all infrastructure projects within his power/jurisdiction from planning stage to implementation to completion since it is incumbent upon him as Municipal Engineer of the LGU to “administer, coordinate, supervise, and control the construction, maintenance, improvement, repair of roads, bridges, and other engineering and public works projects of the local government unit concerned” pursuant to Section 477 of RA 7160.  The MPDC should be furnished with the said report as input to the required report of COA;
Direct the Project Heads/Managers of all non-infrastructure PPAs to prepare and maintain a Monthly Monitoring Report for submission to the Office of the MPDC;
Direct the Municipal Engineer and Project Heads/Managers to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant on the costs incurred of the projects for inclusion in their respective Monthly Monitoring Report; and
Require all concerned officials to adhere strictly to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013, copy attached.

We recommend that management should;
a. Require the accountant to prepare the monthly Report on the Receipt and Utilization of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management (DRRM) fund and submit to the COA Auditor thru the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (LDRRMO) every 15th day of the month.
b. LDRRM Officers must strictly comply with the accounting and reporting requirements stipulated in RA 10121 and COA Circular No. 2012-002, dated September 12, 2012, to ensure that the financial information are appropriately taken up in the books and properly presented in the financial statements with adequate disclosures.
